## Fix — idle-timeout edit-lock was silently re-granted on the next navigation

### Context

Follow-up to the activity-based lease change: after the inactivity lease lapsed
the browser correctly went read-only, **but the lock row was never released** —
the user stayed the recorded holder. Since this is a multi-page app, any
reload / menu navigation re-ran `initEditLock` → `GET /domain/edit-lock`, whose
non-forcing acquire hands a free/own lock straight back to the loader (a stale
lease is still granted to its owner). Net effect: the timeout was undone by the
next click — edit mode came back automatically, defeating the whole point. Fix:
on an **inactivity** timeout, actually release the lock server-side and remember
(per version) that this browser gave editing up, staying read-only across
reloads until the user **explicitly resumes**.

### Changes

1. `src/front/static/global/js/edit-lock.js`
   - New `expireByIdle()` (called from the idle watcher instead of `onLeaseLost`
     directly): `POST /domain/edit-lock/release` (frees the lock immediately for
     other users) + a per-version **sticky flag** in `sessionStorage`
     (`ob:editLockExpired = "folder\u0000version"`), then the usual read-only +
     expired-banner teardown.
   - `initEditLock` now honours the sticky flag: when the status check re-grants
     `mode == "edit"` for the *same* version we timed out on, it re-releases the
     lock and stays read-only (expired banner) instead of resuming editing. A
     `view` result (someone else took it) or `none` clears the flag.
   - Expired banner button relabelled **Reload → "Resume editing"**; it now
     clears the sticky flag before reloading, so an explicit resume is the only
     path that re-acquires the still-free lock. A lease lost to a take-over /
     stale reclaim still flips to read-only via `onLeaseLost` (no sticky — it is
     already gone).
2. `src/back/objects/registry/lockmgt/EditLockService.py`
   - `status(...)` now returns the loaded `folder` / `version` alongside the
     lock block so the client can scope the sticky "expired" state to the exact
     version (prevents a timeout on domain A from suppressing edit on domain B).

### Modified files

- `src/front/static/global/js/edit-lock.js`
- `src/back/objects/registry/lockmgt/EditLockService.py`

### Test result

- `node --check src/front/static/global/js/edit-lock.js` → clean; JS lint clean.
- `uv run pytest -q -m "not scenario"` → **2971 passed, 275 skipped, 5
  deselected** in ~21s (status-shape tests use key access, unaffected by the new
  `folder` / `version` keys).


## Fix — allow comments & task creation in read-only / view mode

### Context

In any read-only mode (`read-only-locked` from the single-editor lock,
`role-viewer`, or `read-only-version`) the discussion offcanvas was half-broken:
the "Comment" / "New task" buttons stayed clickable but the comment textarea and
the task title / assignee / due-date fields were greyed out and unusable — so
you could open the forms but not fill them in. This is wrong: comments and tasks
are **collaboration, not domain editing**. Their `/comments` + `/tasks`
endpoints are neither domain-role- nor lifecycle-status- nor edit-lock-gated
server-side (confirmed in `PermissionMiddleware`: `/comments` is not in
`_DOMAIN_SCOPED_PREFIXES`, not `_STATUS_GATE_*`, so viewers and locked-out users
already pass the backend). The block was purely the frontend `permissions.css`
generic input/textarea/select gate catching the offcanvas fields.

### Changes

1. `src/front/static/global/js/comments-panel.js`
   - Tagged the discussion-offcanvas fields with a `data-collab` marker: the
     comment compose textarea, the reply textarea, and the task form's title
